{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dowe_ver01/data/sn92073229/00332891868/1958032401/0232.xml":{"full_text":"Page Two\nThe Chapel Hill Weekly\nChapel Hill, North Carolina\n186 E. Rowaipr Telephone 9-1271 or M<l\nPaUbhed Every Monday and Thnraday\nBy The Chapel Hill Pabltahing Coaipany. In;.\nLouis Graves Contr.buting Editor\nJot Jones Managing Editor\nOrville Campbell General Manager\nJames E Critcher Advertwinp Manager\nCharlton Campbell Mechanical Supt\ntotervd a* Mcond-clnai matter February M. 118. at\nthe poet olf*c* at Chapel Hill. North Carolina, under\nthe act of March 3, l\u00bb7g\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nIn Orange Connty, Year $4.00\n(6 month $2.26 3 months, $1.60)\nOutside of Orange County by the Year:\n'\"States of N. C., Va_, and S. C. 4.50\nOther States rt><J Dint. of Columbia 6.00\nCanada, Mexico, South America 7.00\nEurope 7 A0\nCommunity Giving\nThe Chapel Hill Community Chest\nfund drive reached about three-fourths\nof its goal this year. Some communities\nare experiencing even more difficulty\nin meeting the quota.\nThe Community Council, which spon\nsors the Chest, receives all requests\nfrom organizations wanting to solicit\ndonations (except the American Red\nCross and the various health organiza\ntions). The Council then reviews the\nbudgets and sets a quota for each or\nganization in the Council and the total\nis the Chest goal of the year.\nThe Community Chest idea was\nadopted by communities because people\ndid not want to be bothered with a new\ndrive every few days and because so\nlicitors could not be found to make the\ndoor-to-door calls in the individual cam\npaigns.\nThe American Red Cross, a quaai\ngovernmental organization, could not\nlet a Community Council determine its\nquota and so insisted on having its own\nfund drive. As health associations were\norganized, each having its national\nheadquarters, they, too, maintained\nthat the quota system was not adequate\nfor their needs. The TP. Association\nadopted the Christmas Sea! method of\nsoliciting by mail and the Society for\nCrippled Children and Adults did th<\nsame thing by using Easter Seals. The\nother health organizations found\nenough people interested in the causes\nto get the necessary solicitors, and to\nget the donations.\nWith the failure of the Community\nChest, many organizations in it will\nmake special appeals for help.\nThus we find ourselves in the dilem\nma of being called weekly to be a solid\ntor and being asked almost daily to\nmake a contribution to an agency.\nPerhaps the solution lies in having\na many-in-one-and-a-one-in-many solici\ntation. This would involve having one\nsolicitor ask contributions for many or\nganizations all at one time. Thus the\nHeart Association would supply the\nsolicitor an envelope and the R\u00ab-erea\ntion Commission would supply an en\nvelope and each of the other organiza\ntions would do the same. Only one\ndrive would be jiermitted during the\nyear. Only one solicitor would call at\na home. Yet the donor could use any\none or all of the envelopes according to\nhis desire to give.\nThis procedure would enable the don\nor to give, and give precisely as much\nas he wanted to, to the organizations\nof his choice. It would restore real in\ncentive to giving on the part of the\ndonor. On the other hand the agency\nasking for contributions would not gain\nby having a separate drive. If people\ndon\u2019t want to contribute to an organiza\ntion, it is their privilege not to.\nThe School Districts Election\nThe Orange County Board of Com\nmissioners is in possession of a joint\npetition of the Orafge County and the\nChapel Hill Boards of Education re\nquesting that an election be called in\nthe White Cross and Carrboro School\nDistricts to determine whether the cit\nizens of those districts want to join the\nChapel Hill School District.\nThe time of the election has not\nbeen set.\nBefore the 1955 School Assignment\nLaw was passed, the Chapel Hill\nSchools were responsible for educating\nall the high school and the NegTo ele\nmentary school pupils in these sections.\nSince then the Chapel Hill schools have\ncontinued to educate them, but without\nlegal responsibility.\nThe Chapel Hill School District has a\nspecial 15 cent school tax (the enabling\nact specified that up to 20 cents could\nbe levied). Because the White Cross\nand Carrboro districts do not have such\na tax, many Chapel Hillians have ask\ned their school board to (1) demand a\nmerger of school districts and have a\nspecial tax levied on all citizens in the\nenlarged district; or (2) ask that\nCarrboro and White Cross pupils be\nwithdrawn from Chapel Hill schools.\nIt is because of this dilemma that\nthe people of Carrboro and White\nCross recently asked the Orange Coun\nty Board of Education to request a\nreferendum on the issue.\nAbout 41 teachers of the Chapel\nHill schools are currently teaching pu\npils from the Carrboro and White\nCross Districts. These teachers cannot\nbe rehired for the coming year until it\nis determined what pupils will be in\nthe schools.\nAlso, in accordance with the stand\nards of the Thape! Hill School District,\nfull-time librarians would have to be\nhired for each of the two new schools\n(White Cross and Carrboro), teachers\nwould have to be hired to permit full\ntime principals in each school (current\nly the principals of these schools also\nteach classes), and other provisions\nwould have to be made.\nMeeting these responsibilities will\ntake time-. For this reason it is urgent\nthat the* election date be set and the\nwishes of the people be determined at,\nan early date.\nMaking a I .est Turn\nComplaints have been received by\nthe Weekly that traffic is unduly snarl\ned at certain intersections during the\nmorning and evening rush hours. One\nsuch place of congestion is the inter\nsection of Pittsboro Road and the new\nStadium Road; another is the intersec\ntion of Cameron Avenue and South Co\nlumbia Street. There are others.\nMuch of the traffic difficulty is\ncaused by drivers\u2019 not knowing how to\nmake left turns. A driver wishing to\nmake a left hand turn should proceed\nunder the light so as to be ready to\nswing into the right lane the moment\noncoming traffic stops. But the vast\nmajority of the drivers in this com\nmunity apparently do not know this.\nSuch a driver waits at the entrance of\nthe intersection on which the left turn\nis to be made, thus not only blocking\nall through and right-hand traffic be\nhind him, but also often missing his\nchance to turn while the light is green.\nThus the cars behind such a driver con\ntinue to be added to the already long\nline.\nUnfortunately, the State Highway\nDepartment\u2019s manual on safe driving\ndoes not mention the problem of mak\ning left turns, so people pass the driv\ners\u2019 test without knowing that they\ndon\u2019t know the correct procedure.\nThe other primary causes of traflic\ncongestion on a narrow street are park\ning \u201cjust to run an errand,\u201d the wait\ning for a prospective passenger to come\nfrom his or her office, or often just\ngiving a departing passenger time to\nquit talking. It takes only a few min\nutes of blocking a lane of traffic to\ncause a traffic jam. Yet it is done\ndaily; done by people who shout epi\nthets at others for doing the same\nthing.\nThey Finally Said It\n(SmiLhfitid Herald;\nU. S. business has been aware of the\neconomic slump for months, but public\nuse of the words \"slump\" or \"recession\u201d\nhas been taboo until now. Business\nwriters have been hesitant about call\ning the slump what it is, as a bather\nunaccustomed to the surf is hesitant\nabout getting into a cold ocean.\nHere\u2019s the way the gradualists among\nbusiness writers let us in on the bad\n(or should we say \"unwelcome\u201d?)\nnews:\nSeptember 15\u2014\u201c The mood among\nbusinessmen who look to next year is\none of caution. Now nobody is alarmed.\nSome of the economic signs are just\nuncertain.\u201d\n(Mober 16\u2014\u201c Business is in a level\ning-off period. We are not having a\nrecession, as some say.\u201d\nNovember I\u2014\u2018\"Eisenhower\u2019s econo\nmic advisers are not convinced of a\ndownward business trend. They only\nnote some weaknesses as well as strong\nfactors in the economy. Thig is an ad\njustment, not a recession.\u201d\nNovember 16\u2014\u201c Business is slightly\noff. No bust. No recession. It\u2019s just\nthat there is nothing in the offing to\nlift the level of business.\u201d\nDecember I\u2014\u201c Business leaders agree\nthat we are in for some decline in busi\nness. Whether the decline will last six\nmonths or 12 months is not certain.\nBut this is still not a recession.\u201d\nJanuary I\u2014\u201c The business decline\nTHE CHAPEL HILL WEEKLY\n\u201cStop The Bear! Slop The Bear But Gently!\u201d\nNow and Then B> Bill Prouty\nScores as times down through the\nears people have said to me: \"Oh,\nyou\u2019re from Chapel Hill. How I wish\nI lived there!\u201d or: \u201cYou\u2019re so lucky to\niive in Chapt-l Hill. We\u2019ve often thought\nof moving there to live.\u201d\nJ\u2019heir faces would light up when they\ntold of some happy ffcperience they\nhad when they were in school here, or\nwhile, on a visit here. And they w'ould\nprobe me for additional news about the\ntown and its people.\nAnd never in my nearly forty years\nin Chapel Hill have J ever seen a per\nson or a family happily anticipating\nmoving aw\u2019ay from the village. There\nmust have been such j**rsons, of course,\nbut I never ran into them.\nThere\u2019s little wonder that people\nare enthusiastic about living here.\nHere is a town which appeals to people\nof a great variety of interests. Here\nis a town which appeal- to people of all\nages.\nChajs'l Hill is a Find of three-ring\ncircus in which there is something go\ning on at all times. A basketball game,\na lecture, a symposium, a convention,\nan art exhibit, a debate, a concert, a\nballet, a Playmaker production, a stu\ndent meeting. Boys\u2019 State, a discussion\ngroup, a foreign language group meet\ning, a football game, a dance, an auc\ntion, a Boy Scout meeting, a basketball\ngame, a high school play, a PTA meet\ning, a FYiends of the Library meeting,\na party at the Carolina Inn, an original\ntelevision or radio play, a departmental\nmeeting\u2014something for persons of ev\nery interest every night of the year.\nA three-ring circus lovingly staked\nout on a little hill of majestic oaks and\ntall, murmuring pines and with the\ngreat sky for a roof (albeit a little\nleaky in the fall), and with roads from\nthe north, east, south and west leading\nthrough free and unobstructed gates.\nChapel Hill\u2014a paradise for man\u2019s\nwill likely continue for at least six\nmonths. It\u2019s to be worse than any de\ncline since before World War 11. But\nno depression. Hardly a recession.\u201d\nJanuary 26\u2014\u201c The slump is the real\nMcCoy. It\u2019s not a bad recession. But\nthe boom is over. And the news will\nget worse before it gets better. Pre\npare for the shock.\u201d\nThe business writers, at long last,\nreluctantly, have given us the ugly\nfacts of economic life, and their ver\nsion of the facts rfins a bit contrary\nto the somewhat rosy estimate of the\neconomic situation promulgated the\nother day by President Eisenhower.\nWell, what the country ought to have\nis the truth. Neither false pessimism\nnor false optimism will serve us. Real\nism should be a strong ally in warding\noff any threat of real depression.\nmost cherished product, his children,\nand his best friends, the dogs. Here\nboth groups, singularly or together,\nroarri the campus and its facilities in\ncomplete freedom and safety, going\nwhere they wish, doing what they want\nto do.\nChaj* 1 Hill\u2014a town in which scho\nlars and everyday citizens enjoy a so\ncial relationship wdiich, for its genuine\nnaturalness, is probably unsurpassed\nin any community in the United States,\nIn a word, Chapel Hill is a fascinat\ning place in which to live because it\nis now and always dared to be, a place\nof unique quality.\nA town to be unique must be differ\nent in a nice sort of way. But unique\nness necessitates independence, and\nindependence is the most costly of all\nattainments.\nAnd now comes the possibility, nay,\nthe probability, that the business sec\ntion of Chapel Hill will be plastered\nwith that hideous coin-chewing Cy\nclops, the parking meter.\nThey are, I am told, great revenue\ngetters. And the town of Chapel Hill\nneeds money, as what town doesn\u2019t.\nChapel Hill, I\u2019m tdld, is the only\ntown in North Carolina of its popula\ntion class without parking meters.\nChapel Hill, I\u2019m told, must have this\nrevenue to secure off-street parking\nfacilities.\nThe Only thing I know about parking\nproblems is that it\u2019s hard for me to find\na parking place. But the reason for\nthis is usually because I\u2019m too darned\nlazy to walk from where there is an\navailable parking place to where I\nwant to go. That, and the fact that\nthere are too many automobiles\u2014and\nthat\u2019s like saying \u201cThe trouble with us\nAmericans is that we have too much\nmoney.\u201d Maybe we do. But how can\npaying for parking possibly solve the\nparking problems, or laziness?\nAnd the very fact that Chapel Hill\nis the only town in North Carolina in\nits population class which has so far\neschewed this great opportunity for\nlegal extortion, is reason enough why\nit should continue to do so.\nChapel Hill IS the unique town of\nNorth Carolina, and for our own good,\nboth esthetically and financially, we\nshould keep it that way. Don't forget,\npeople come to Chapel Hill to live be\ncause it is different. And when they\ncome here they spend money here, and\nwhen they spend money here, the Town\nof Chapel Hill gets its rightful share\nof it. In the long run, it might pay us\nto keep our town different (including\nno parking meters) even though the\ninitial cost seems great.\nParking meters are just not com\npatible with the type of living for\nwhich Chapel Hill is noted.\nI Like Chapel Hill\nBy Billy Arthur\nEverything is showing the handiwork of nature.\nBirds are flitting, flowers are blooming, \"and all nature\nseems to be clothing herself in a most beautiful\nher bridal robes of springtime.\u201d\nThat, however, I can\u2019t say for the women\u2019s new'\nfashions. As for mine. I\u2019m going around in last year\u2019s\nsuit and a pair of shoes that look second hand..\nMuch already has been said by men about the lat\nest women\u2019s styles, but everyone has overlooked what\nthe women themselves say: they are blaming the men\nfor the changes and for their constantly trying some\nthing new. They've always done that.\nIn the 19th century, they said they gave up hoop\nskirts because the men complained that the hoops bash\ned their shins.\nThey put on bustles, then said they discarded\nthem because the men said bustles made women look\nlike an old barn yard hen that was fit only for roast\ning and chicken salad.\nThey then went for pull-backs, and the men said\nthe dresses looked like bags tied to a stick.\nSo the women donned skirts that struck them just\nabove the ankles, but heard remarks about their feet.\nAnd the girls with big feet said that style had to go.\nNext, they put on long dresses again, and the\nmen joked them for sweeping the streets and stirring\nup gerifcs. _\nDme the 1920\\5, and the dresses got so shor| a\nmoth couldn\u2019t find an apartment or a place to eat.\nAnd that\u2019s when some women discovered other\nwomen were bowlegged, and the other women didn\u2019t\nlike it. They came out for longer skirts. And ankles\ndisappeared.\nMen complained again. They knew women were\nrolling their hose, hut they didn't know where.\nSo the dress designers went to work inching up\n\u2022the hemline. When they got that leveled off, they\nstarted work on the necklines. They scooped \u2019em and\nthey V\u2019d \u2019em.\nAnd men complained again. Something had to be\ndone so they could keep their eyes off their secretaries\nand get some work accomplished.\nNow what do we have?\nWe\u2019ve got the sack look. When our wives get\ntheir clothes on, we can\u2019t tell whether they\u2019re going to\n(Continued on Page 7)\nCHAPEL HILL CHAFF\n(Continued from Page i;\nworked our way from here to Apex before we had four\nmatched wheels and all the other parts we needed.\u201d\n\u201cWho put it together for you?\u201d I asked.\n\"We did it ourselves,\u201d Don said. \u201cRight here in\nthe restaurant. The cloth for the top came from\nBerman\u2019s Store, but we cut it out and sewed it our\nselves.\u201d\nDon also explained the operation of the open char\ncoal grill, where the diners can see their steaks being\nbroiled. A lot of them have been doing just that. The\nplace has been packed every night since it opened.\nSPEED-SAFETY SKILL\ni^EgANnl\nPReacmPTiMM I jfl\nPhone 101\nfOne Mile Out Durham Hwy.\nAnd You\u2019re at...\nj IV S\nlife},\ni Horae of Uie Finest\nSTEAKS BARBEQUE\nCHICKEN SEAFOOD\nOpen 4 p.m. (11 ajn. Sundays) Till 12\nMonday. March 24, 1958","height":"26528","width":"19901"}}
